window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section A>1","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"1","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"JOHN K. KARGBO: Let Me Die Alone    Comment on the character of Yoko in the play.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Madam Yoko is the main character in the play. She is the queen and leader of the Senehun people and the Mende Chiefdom. She takes over the throne after the poisoning of Gbanya, her husband and leader of the people.    Yoko's character is resilient and formidable in the play. Despite knowing that her husband was poisoned by some unscrupulous elements who may want to do the same to her, Yoko seizes the mantle to the throne from Lamboi and his cohort, and proceeds to become the leader of the people. Even as she has secured the throne, she does not relent in being vigilant and strong for her people. One cannot also but see the formidability of Yoko when she alone confronts Lamboi and Musa as they plan to enthrone Lamboi after Gbanya's death.    Also, Madam Yoko is the tragic hero of the play. The play is seen as a tragedy because it has tragic elements. However, it varies a little from Classical tragedy. While the play does not follow the Classical tragic plot, Madam Yoko is still seen as a tragic hero whose circumstance pushes to commit suicide in order to stamp her integrity into the history of the Senehun people. She is tragic in the sense that she does not deserve what happens to her in the play: the accusation that she killed Jeneba for ritual purposes and Governor Rowe's division of the kingdoms without informing her. Of course, just as in a tragedy, the play ends on a sad note: in the death of Yoko.    Finally, Yoko stands as a symbol of resistant to the British colonial administration which swept through sub-Saharan African countries in the wake of colonialism. Yoko stands tall, not scared, as Gbanya is being beaten. After her husband's death, she welcomes the governor's representative but does not grovel at his feet. Her act of suicide is a symbol of resistance to the colonial administration of her era.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section A>2","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"2","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"JOHN K. KARGBO: Let Me Die Alone  What challenges is Mende chiefdom confronted with in the play?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Madam Yoko is the leader of Mende chiefdom. She takes over the mantle after the death of her husband. From the beginning of the play to the end of the play, the people of Senehun encounter different challenges. These challenges are either as a result of internal issues or external issues.    One of these challenges is the overthrowing of Gbanya's regime. Lamboi and Musa connive at killing the king, and they succeed in doing so after Gbanya has been beaten by Governor Rowe's men. A further extension of this particular challenge is Yoko's having to be suspicious every time after ascending the throne. Generally, the ruler and the ruled are suspicious of each other.    Another challenge that the people had to face is the British colonial administration. The people are being ruled by proxy and they watch as Gbanya, their king, is being beaten by Governor Rowe's soldiers. Even after Gbanya's death, and Yoko has become the leader, Governor Rowe still divides her kingdom without consulting her. This is quite painful because she helps the governor contain those people who have refused to pay the tax imposed by the governor.    Again, the tax imposed by the governor is another instance of challenge faced by the people. The imposition of the compulsory housing levy is done after Yoko takes over the mantle of leadership. Yoko handles the situation by fishing out rebels and making them face the consequences of rebelling.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section A>3","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"3","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"WOLE SOYINKA: The Lion and the Jewel    Why does Lakunle lose Sidi to Baroka?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"In the play, The Lion and the Jewel, Soyinka portrays Sidi as an archetype of an integral part of the Yoruba tradition - chastity. In the unfolding events addressing the clash of values, Sidi's characterisation undergirds the tenacity with which the culture of bride price is held important in the African marriage custom - in the Yoruba tradition. It is against this that Lakunle's civilisation is rejected as he fouls his chance of engagement to Sidi in the play.     Lakunle argues that Sidi's cultural belief is barbaric and retrogressive. He questions the essence of bride price when the world is so civilised. He plans taking her out of Ilujinle if she accepts his proposal. She fits in the modern lifestyle so well. The implication I their dialogue is that we see two contradictory beliefs arguing the superiority of their values. Also that, Lakunle does not regard the this requirement because he sees Sidi's beauty all in the light of the same westernisation Sidi deems unbecoming. Although Lakunle is progressive in exposure, Sidi's makes no sense of his disavowal of what her culture demands so long marriage is concerned. As such, she will not marry a man who is not ready to meet the demand of her honorable tradition.     Further, Lakunle loses Sidi to Baroka's position. Baroka becomes a formidable obstacle to Lakunle's chance, being an influential viceroyal chieftain (Baale) whose influence is revealed as an imperial control. The reader is made to understand how bleak the possibility of marrying Sidi is for Lakunle the moment Baroka declares his interest in her. Since Baroka always gets what he wants, even at all cost, Lakunle's hope shrinks. To further undermine Lakunle's aim, Sadiku, the head of Baroka's harem, is a persistent persuader. It is needless to say that her influence works on Sidi to make her agree to meet Baroka, against her erstwhile decision. Sadiku dispels Sidi's reservation for the Baale by revealing that he is impotent. Upon knowing this, Sidi wants to go to the palace with a view to mocking the chief. When Lakunle interrupts the discussion, he is not recognised. He quickly senses Baroka's 'game' more so. He finds his choice in competition with the Baale's, which frizzles his desire to an irretrievable loss.     To that end, in the resolution of the conflict, Sidi falls prey of the Lion (Baroka)'s cunningness in the reality of which she loses her virginity. When she comes out of Baroka's room and breaks the news to the duo of Sadiku and Lakunle who have been apprehensive, they are surprised at the chief's egregious act. On the minute still, Lakunle reaffirms his love for Sidi and promises to marry her regardless. Sidi refuses. She must marry her 'husband', the man to whom she has lost her virginity. She - and Sadiku - leaves to make the wedding preparation for the marriage between her and Baroka.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section A>4","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"4","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"WOLE SOYINKA: The Lion and the Jewel  Examine the theme of love and marriage in the play.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The play, in its treatment of the conflict/clash of values, explores prominently the theme of love and marriage as a spectacle of the author's treatment of reality. The play centring on the 'struggle' between Baroka and Lakunle for Sidi implicitly addresses the notion about marriage within the look of tradition. The idea of love and marriage, we see, thus facilitates the resolution of the (main) conflict in the plot.    On the hand, Lakunle's westernised belief is refuted by the high-handedness of cultural marriage values. He must abide by the dictate of the existing tradition if he wants to marry Sidi. But he debases this with his 'alien' values. Love means the payment of bride price and vice versa. In the argument that ensues between Lakunle and Sidi, the latter emphasises that if she marries without her bride price paid, then she marries cheap, and such is never befitting. She tries to convince Lakunle to her claims. Also, that he loves her does not - and will not - change the traditional belief. We begin to see the definition of love in the African marriage setting: that a woman is with more than the man's professing of love without action; that bride price is an inseparable part of marriage custom. A compulsory step at that. Since Lakunle disbelieves this, then his acclaimed love for Sidi is not genuine and marriage cannot happen. The author shows: African marriage custom demands, above all, that bride price be paid, which is the proof of love.     On the other hand, the author uses irony to show the condition for marriage in the African setting: Baroka who is ready to pay the bride price owns the bride. Although this happens in an obscene manner, love is portrayed as the readiness to marry a woman according to the standard of tradition. Sidi eventually unarguable belongs to Baroka who cunningly takes her virginity. This brings to the fore the ribaldry common in the African society, especially among the traditional elites, which precipitates marriage, as seen in how Baroka gets Sidi as wife. While Lakunle's love for Sidi is true and genuine, Baroka's is ribald and borne by his influence. Baroka proves his 'love' to Sidi by marrying her as custom demands; Lakunle fouls up his chance by countering that with his civilisation. Although Sidi could have accepted Lakunle's marriage proposal, she is obliged to marry Baroka who does the right thing.     To the trio of Lakunle, Sidi and Baroka in the love triangle, love and marriage are understood differently. To Lakunle, it is the outlook of civilisation; to Sidi, the payment of bride price; to Baroka, the possibility of influence. Soyinka bears on these differences to bring the play to resolution. He explores love and marriage as an instrumental force in highlighting his subject matter.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section B>5","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"5","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"JOHN OSBORNE: Look Back in Anger    Compare Jimmy and Cliff as friends.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Jimmy Porter was a twenty five years old who lived in Britain, in the industrial midlands. He is educated, well read and works in a factory and also tends a sweet shop. He is never tired of criticising the British society which denied him many opportunities because he belonged to the working class. He was an honest person and was proud of it. He was very cruel in his verbal attacks on his wife Alison and friend Cliff. He is ego centric and is oblivious to his own faults. He criticises his wife but has no worry about his affair with his wife's friend Helena. He cannot empathize with his wife when she grieves over the loss of her baby. He accepts Alison only after realising that she had suffered enough like him.    Cliff Lewis is a friend of Jimmy and belonged to the working class like Jimmy. Cliff is a gentle person and does not have the fire or wit of Jimmy. Cliff is fond of Alison and appreciates her housekeeping efforts. It is Cliff who bandages the burns on Alison's hands and not Jimmy. Cliff is the only character in the play who understands the feelings of other and he is the first to see Helena's intention behind breaking Alison's marriage. He dislikes Helena and moves out when she moves in.    Cliff acts as the foil of Jimmy. While Jimmy is an aggressive, go-getting kind of person who hates passiveness, Cliff is a passive character who loves the status quo.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section B>6","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"6","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"JOHN OSBORNE: Look Back in Anger  Discuss Jimmy Porter's sense of alienation in the play.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Jimmy Porter feels alienated from both his wife and society in general.  He is a struggling middle class working man who is bored and confined by his monotonous life.  His wife Alison has come to accept life, silently bearing any and all burdens. Jimmy feels resentful of Alison's aloofness and indifferent demeanor and strikes out at her to get a reaction.    Jimmy is an angry man who feels that his opportunities in life were shaped by his middle class upbringing.  Alison's brother Nigel has a university degree and is a member of Parliament.  Jimmy hates him for his connection to the world.  A connection that he knows that he will never have.  Jimmy is a character who contemplates the world beyond the dimensions of his own existence.  He cannot find anyone to talk to about the injustices or curiosities he feels about life.    Part of Jimmy's alienation is from a general feeling in Great Britain in the 1950s when the ordinary British citizen felt passed over by a government who had promised prosperity for everyone.  Instead, following WWII, in which London was destroyed, the British people struggle with new threats and a country put back together with a socialist system in place that is designed to keep everyone equal, except the very rich who remain the upper class, high above the ordinary citizen.  Jimmy resents all of this and knows that it will never change.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section B>7","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"7","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"AUGUST WILSON: Fences    Consider Raynell's contribution to the plot.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Raynell is the child born by Alberta to Troy in the play. Although Alberta dies from childbirth, the child remains alive. The character of the child alone contributes a lot to the development of the plot and the issues discussed therein.    Consider, for instance, the issues of fidelity and truthfulness in the play. Troy Maxson is shown as a character who romances infidelity and is not truthful in his dealings. The birth of Raynell is used to reveal his infidelity, which will otherwise have been hidden from Sarah and the rest of his family. Of course, Cory is the one used to reveal that Troy is pocketing the money meant for Gabriel, his mentally-disturbed brother. So, Cory also serves as a development tool to the plot in his own right.    Raynell also serves as a token of separation between Troy Maxson and Sarah Maxson. Troy might have been a imperfect, mistake-prone husband and father, but that does not warrant the separation which occurs in the play. However, Sarah uses Raynell as a token of separation between her and her husband. She says Troy is now a \"womanless man\" because of Baby Raynell.    On the flip side of the coin, Raynell serves as a uniting factor between Sarah and her husband, and between Cory and the rest of the family, even though the uniting occurs after troy's death. It is because there is nobody to take care of Baby Raynell that Sarah agrees to take care of her and be a mother to her. She also does not leave Troy because of the baby.    Of course, Cory comes home after Troy dies, but it is with Raynell that he finds what connects him to their father: Raynell and Cory sing one of Troy's father's blues songs. And it was a moment of nostalgia, reminiscence and togetherness.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section B>8","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"8","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"AUGUST WILSON: Fences  Comment on the appropriateness of the title, Fences.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"August Wilson's Fences is a play set in the 1950s America when blacks were migrating North in order to find greener pastures. The title is a symbol connoting division and separation: a fence separates two things; it alienates two things from each other; it divides a whole into two. In some cases, a fence can even divide into more than two. However, in this play, we have the plurality of the word: fences. This means that there is more than one fence in the play. When this claim is examined, it is discovered that it is not only true but also concluded from the various instances in the play.    One of such instances is the dichotomy between white players and black players in the baseball league. Even though black players outperformed white players, they still were not recognised in the major league, forcing black players to be confined to their own league. Troy Maxson himself mentioned different instances of his outperforming major white baseball players who, yet, were deified. The bitterness caused by this fence remained in Troy until his son, Cory, is about to be recruited by his college football team. Apparently, the prejudice spanned more than just the baseball league. Troy refuses to consent to Cory's joining the football team and this creates another fence in the play.    When Cory does not get his father to consent to his joining the football team, he leaves home and joins the US Marine Corps. For eight years, Cory and his father stay apart, either one not knowing the well-being of the other. It can be conclusively stated that it is the larger fence of racial prejudice in the baseball league which extends and creates this smaller fence between Cory and his father.    Another instance which corroborates the plurality of the title and affirms its rightfulness is the job disparity between white garbage workers and black garbage workers. For a number of years, Troy Maxson worked for the garbage company, yet, he still remained a garbage collector while whites were automatically given the job of drivers. This creates not only a disparity between the two races but also a deep-seated belittling for black garbage collectors. Fortunately, Troy is able to fight for his right and he becomes a driver.    From what these highlighted instances, one can see that there are more than one fence in the play. Of course, one should never think of the title as referring to the actual fence in the play; the fence has metaphorical meanings for 1950 America. The playwright has done well in representing the issues of that era using symbolism which can be understood by literary critics and the general readership.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section C>9","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"9","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN POETRY","question":"Discuss the personification of rage in the poem, \"Raider of the Treasure Trove\".","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Lade Wosornu's \"Raider of Treasure Trove\" can be said to revolve around the reason for man's existence: to be happy or fulfilled. The persona opines that those who are happy are likely to achieve success than those who are not. He therefore presents life as a journey where one should seek happiness and eschew rage. That is, rage constitutes one of the impediments that can restrict a person's happiness and even cut short the person's life - \"rob you of your life\". This essay will therefore discuss how rage is personified in the text.    To personify means to give an inanimate or abstract object human qualities. Here, rage can be regarded as abstract because it is a quality that can neither be seen nor touched. In the text, rage is personified as it is given human qualities in a bid to show the effect it can have on an individual. Important to note is that none of these effects can be deemed as positive; rather, rage is presented as a killer, thief and other epithets.    Firstly, rage is regarded as chief of all the things that could rob a person of his life: that is, a killer. By this, the persona unequivocally places rage as a destroyer who must never be entertained by anyone. This pattern of branding rage a destroyer is further seen in the subsequent lines where rage is given the ability to drag a thing - \"rage drags rags\". Undoubtedly, the image created in this extract is one of destruction; that is, instead of bringing about positivity, rage brings negativity, dirt and destruction, all of which are metaphorically marked as \"rags\".    In addition, rage is regarded as \"a thief\". It is one that steals laughter, sweetness and light. Of course, the ability of rage to perform these tasks that are reserved for humans constitutes a personification of rage. Apart from being a thief, rage is also regarded an \"enemy of equanimity\". Equanimity suggests a calm state of mind that means that you do not become angry or upset, especially in difficult situations. Rage, therefore, erodes this calmness by causing trouble and spelling or bringing about calamity.     The persona, thus, admonishes against rage. He warns humans of the consequences of rage by personifying rage as a killer, thief and bringer of calamity. In conclusion, this essay has been able to comment on the personification of rage in Lade Wosornu's \"Raider of Treasure Trove\".","marks":"25","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section C>10","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"10","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN POETRY","question":"Show how Africa suffered and survives still in Agostinho Neto's \"The Grieved Lands of Africa\".","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Agostinho Neto's \"The Grieved Lands of Africa\" is one that retells the suffering experienced by Africa and its inhabitants under the cruel oppression of her colonial masters. The poem graphically depicts events such as colonialism and slavery, and shows the inimical effects they have had on Africa. However, despite all these nefarious acts done, Africa and her inhabitants still survive. The reason for their survival is owing to the dogged spirit of every African. On this note, this essay will show how Africa suffered and how it has managed to survive the hardship meted by the colonialists.    Of course, it is no news that the coming of Western powers caused untold hardship to Africans. In this text, the suffering experienced by Africa is brought to the fore through the anaphora - \"The grieved lands...\" Another way this was done was through the Trans-Atlantic Slave Trade where many Africans were ferried across the Atlantic to serve as slaves in plantations. This act is well captured by the persona in the first stanza where he made reference to \"ancient and modern slave\" and \"...degrading sweat of impure dance of other seas\". The reference to \"sea\" can be seen as an allusion to the slave trade that occurred across the Atlantic. Thus, it can be justifiably said that Africa suffered as a result of slavery.    Apart from selling off many Africans into slavery, Africa was also subjected to colonial humiliation. This humiliation is evinced through the way the colonialists came to Africa and imposed their will on its inhabitants. Because these colonialists believed their ways to be superior to African cultures, they forcefully made Africans to abandon indigenous cultures for westernization. This is aptly portrayed in the text where the persona describes the \"flower\" to have been \"crushed in the forest by the wickedness of the iron and the fire.\" Flower, as used, literally means African ways while \"iron and fire\" represent the destructive tools of the colonial masters. The use of the image of \"iron and fire\" to symbolise the destruction of African values shares great semblance with Kofi Awoonor's \"The Anvil and the Hammer\" where he portrays the colonialists to be blacksmiths who are reshaping African values.    Furthermore, the issue of slavery and colonialism brought about unfair laws that arrested and jailed Africans indiscriminately. Agostinho Neto does not mince words as he describes how the dreams of many Africans are cut short by their incarceration: \"In the dream soon undone in jingling of gaolers keys.\" This imprisonment of Africans further piles up their misery.     Despite all these punishment meted out to Africans, they have still survived. This survivalist attitude of Africans is highlighted in the last four stanzas. Words like \"alive, live and life\" are used to show that the African spirit has not been killed by the hardship it has been subjected to. Also, the repetition of the lines, \"They live\", in the last two stanzas is testament of the fact that Africa still survives.    One way Africa has been able to survive the onslaught of her colonialists is through the doggedness of Africans. Despite all they have suffered, Africans remain steadfast. The African spirit is believed to remain alive in dreams. Dreams, here, symbolise hope. Thus, this hope or optimism about a better future helps African to overcome their tribulations. In fact, the hardship faced in the hands of the colonial masters have only made Africans more resilient; hence, this resilience has been able to aid their survival. The fact that Africans still survive explains why the poet described them as \"imperishable particles\".    In all, despite all the suffering and hardship meted out to Africans, Africa has still managed to survive, and the persona attributes this survivalist attitude of Africans to their doggedness. This essay has therefore been able to comment in how Africa suffered and survived as depicted in Agostinho Neto's \"The Grieved Lands of Africa\".","marks":"25","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section D>11","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"11","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN POETRY","question":"Consider the use of alliteration, assonance and repetition in the poem, \"Binsey Poplars\".","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Analysis of any critical work should involve the consideration of both the elements of form and those of contents. Form, of course, refers to elements such as sound, figurative expression and rhythm while content revolves around the thematic concerns. The elements of form and content are not exclusive because they depend on one another; that is, the formal elements are used to derive the thematic concerns. This essay will therefore comment on the use of sound elements such as alliteration, assonance and repetition in Hopkins' \"Binsey Poplars\". These sound devices will be analysed based on how they are able to project the themes.    \"Binsey Poplars\" can be considered as an ecocritical poem that mourns the felling of poplar trees in Binsey Village. This destruction according to the persona is one that alters the landscape by making it less beautiful and appealing for the generations to come. The persona affinity for these trees is captured through the way he uses endearing terms to describe the trees: \"My aspens dear\". It can therefore be said that this poem revolves around the despoliation of nature.    To perspicuously describe the destruction brought my man on nature, Gerard Hopkins infuses different artistic devices that help to paint vivid pictures of man's destructive acts on nature as well as the consequences. One device that is used to serve this purpose is repetition. For instance, the repetition of \"felled\" in \"All felled, felled, are all felled\" is used to emphasize man's destructive tendencies, thus painting a picture of destruction. The consequence of this felling of poplar trees is that the scenery is changed from something beautiful to something less appealing. The repetition of \"scene\" in the last three lines brings into focus the persona's sadness at the fact that the next generation will not witness the once beautiful scenery. Note that the repetition of various words in this helps to lay emphasis on key issues.    Another major device deployed by the poet is alliteration: the repetition of similar consonant sounds at word-initial position. Alliteration as used in this text helps to add musicality and makes the text pleasurable for reading. One instance of the deployment of alliteration is seen in the extract below when the sound /f/ alliterates:    \"All felled, felled, are all felled;  Of a fresh and following folded rank\"     However, more importantly, it helps to accentuate the thematic concerns. The alliteration above undoubtedly shows the theme of destruction. Other examples of the use of alliteration include: (i) Quelled or Quenched in leaves leaping sun ( Q Alliterates); (ii) shadow that swam or sank (S Allitterate); (iii) wind wandering wind winding bank ( W Alliterates)    Apart from using alliteration, the poet also employs assonance. Assonance refers to the repetition of similar vowel sounds, usually at word-medial position. The use of assonance creates a pleasurable sound pattern as in \"dear...airy\"; \"quelled, quelled... quenched\" ; and \"felled ...felled...felled\". The vowel sounds in these words are all similar.","marks":"25","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Drama and Poetry>Section D>12","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"12","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN POETRY","question":"Comment on the Poet's attitude to death in \"Do Not Go Gentle Into That Good Night\".","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Thomas Dylan's \"Do not Go Gentle into that Good Night\" is a villanelle. It has six stanzas, with the first five having three lines each and the ultimate stanza with four lines. It centres on death and how men should react to it. It can be said to have been written as a form of encouragement to the persona's sick father to strive to stay alive. Important to note is that the persona affirms that death is inevitable; however, he urges everyone not to be accepting towards death. To put simply, the persona is of the opinion that people should fight against death. On this note, this essay will comment on the poet's attitude to death.    As mentioned earlier, this poem in its entirety is pervaded by death and images of death. For instance, \"good night\" is used to mean the \"end of day\", but in this context, it paints a picture of the end of a person's life. Furthermore, expressions such as \"the dying of the light\" also paint vivid images about death. Therefore, the fact that the aforementioned expressions are constantly repeated in the various stanzas of the poem show that death constitutes the focal point of the poet's attention.    The poet's attitude towards death can be said to be one of defiance. He admits in several stanzas that death is an inevitable end to life, but this does not stop him from advising against the placid acceptance of death. The title itself, \"Do not Go Gentle into that Good Night\", strengthens the stance of the poet as he unequivocally instructs against dying peacefully. To the poet, death should not be accepted gently. Thus, it is no coincidence that these very lines are echoed in the last line of some of the stanzas as a form of refrain, thereby giving further credence to the stance taken by the poet persona.    In a bid to show his defiance towards death, the persona cites several sets of people who never accept death. These individuals are classified as \"wise men\", \"good men\", \"wild men\" and \"grave men\". He admits through the wise men that death is unavoidable - \"Though wise men at their end know dark is right\" - but this fact does not make the men any less accommodating to death or the thoughts of dying. By citing these men as examples of those with the right reaction towards death, the persona is able to intensely plead with his addressee, his father, to imitate these men by staying alive.    In conclusion, by urging people to try to stay alive even when death metaphorically calls, the poet is trying to defy nature because death is an unavoidable part of nature. Taking cognizance of the all that have been written, one can justifiably say that the persona's attitude towards death is one of defiance.","marks":"25","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section A>1","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"1","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN PROSE","question":"BUCHI EMECHETA: Second Class Citizen    How are women treated in the novel?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Second Class Citizen is a semi-autobiographical novel that focuses on the oppression of women and racial discrimination in the society. It exposes the significance of the title of the novel, Second Class Citizen, that is, how women are treated as second class citizens while men are considered first class citizens in the Nigeria society. The novel revolves around Adah, the protagonist of the novel, who grows up with the hurdles of life due to her gender and tries to escape by migrating to London. But unfortunately, her dreams are shortened as she faces another problem of second class citizen as well as catering for her children. Women, in this novel, are treated negatively not only by men but also by the society as a whole.     They are regarded as irrelevant creatures who are not meant to be heard in the society, especially in intellectual activities. Many parents, just like in Ibuza, expect a male child to please the people and to show the importance of their families to the society. This makes them feel disappointed when they deliver baby girl because the people do not value the female gender as the male, since they end up getting married no matter their level of education. As seen in the story of Adah, she was considered \"so insignificant\" and a disappointment to her parents because she arrived as a girl when everyone was expecting a boy which made the people unconcerned about recording her birth to the extent that she pitied her parents for giving birth to her.     Apart from that, women receive blame for any evil that befall their families - husbands and children. They are never credited for a job well done, rather their husbands draw all praises to themselves despite the efforts of their wives. For instance, Adah's mother was forced to drink garri at the police station as a punishment for Adah's loss. Francis, Adah's self-centered husband, blames his wife his examination failures. And, the pronoun \"her\" is used to replace \"their\" when the children exhibit bad characters as emulating the mother and grandmother.     The oppression of women heighten as women's education is seen as a means of survival through high cost of bride price. Every male child has the freedom of education for it was regarded as a \"bright future\", while a female child is only permitted to attend school to get bigger dowry from her future husband. The society, as seen in the novel, claims that girls should be taught how to be very useful at early stage in preparation for their suitors. This is because only old men could pay high bride price in which some women find themselves unfortunate rather than being fortunate to be educated as they end up becoming wives of baldies. However, Adah was lucky to escape this dejection because of her ugliness, but she later married a man leading her to poverty.    Moreover, women in this novel are treated to be subjugated to their husbands and in-laws. This occurs especially when such a woman is a literate and earns more money than her husband. Her in-laws make her a fool in the name of \"wife\" and use sugar-coated mouth to get her do their wishes. She, then, becomes a supporter who neglects her dreams to fulfil her husband's and to please her in-laws. To illustrate, Adah thought herself lucky to escape from an unpleasant marriage until she finds herself in another problem where she neglects her dream of travelling abroad to sponsor Francis' education and to please her parents-in-law who use her to get what they want, as seen in Big Pa's advice to Francis illustrated below:     \"Where will she take the money to? Her people?...   The money is for you, can't you see? Let her go and work for    a million Americans and bring their money here, into this house.   It is your luck. You made a good choice in marriage, son.\" (p. 20)  This evidently reveals negative treatment of women inflicted by men for selfish purposes.    Nevertheless, women are treated as sex objects that can be used when it is demanded. It is unfortunate that many women suffer from moral decadence in marriage due to the dissatisfaction of their husbands. Many husbands prefer having sexual intercourse with their girlfriends despite the capability of their wives in satisfying them. And, those wives are not to complain when they find their husbands in such heart-wrenching act, as seen in the character of Adah who knew about Francis' sexual relationship with Turdy but still pretends as if she knows nothing until her son, Vicky, becomes sick.     Asides this, some women are forced to sleep with their husbands any time and receive beatings when they refuse until they give in. Adah is a good example of such women. She suffers from her husband's sentiment about a woman, \"a second-class human\", to the extent that he beats her whenever she refuses to give in when he needs her in bed. Then, he sent her out of bed to wash his clothes and cook for him at the right time, after he is done with her (p. 175).    Lastly, men are free to do whatever they like with their women. They are not reprimanded by the society, rather women have no choice but to accept what is in store for them. For example, women are used as opportunities for African men to boast of their stay in abroad, they do not care about the origin of those women as long as their marriage with them is a consolation and to defend themselves from the shame of not accomplishing their dreams. Women have no right to involve themselves in intelligent conversation for the fear of women domination. In addition, the maltreatment is not only bestowed on women but also on young females, as seen in the characters of Francis and Titi. He only cautions and threatens Titi for speaking Yoruba, but Vicky is never reprimanded. And, this threat inflict fear in the poor girl that she hardly talks to anyone since she can not speak English.     In synopsis, this essay has evidently shown how women are treated in Buchi Emecheta's Second Class Citizen using their symbol of irrelevance, subjugation, fear, and as sexual objects to men as illustrations.","marks":"25","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section A>2","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"2","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN PROSE","question":"BUCHI EMECHETA: Second Class Citizen  Consider Adah's growth in confidence and determination in pursuit of her dreams.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"In Buchi Emecheta's Second Class Citizen, Adah is seen as an embodiment of confidence and determination. She is the main character of this novel who depicts an act of endurance to face the challenges of life since her childhood age. She is determined and confident to be different from other women that are maltreated by the society, through education, as her pursuit of dreams. This pursuit, however, leads her into three important phases of her life, that is, from childhood to adulthood, and from adulthood to motherhood.     It all begins when Adah was birthed to the Ofili family as a female child. She knows she is considered irrelevant to her parents and the society because of her gender which made her pity her parents. The preference of a male child going to school while the opposite gender is given little or no permission to be in school as long as she can read and write. This gender discrimination instigates Adah's confidence and determination to be educated to the extent that she becomes envious and frustrated for not having the same right as her brother, Boy, to be in school.     Surprisingly, Adah's confidence and determination to pursue her dreams grows stronger that she indulges herself in mischiefs. She takes law into her hands by sending herself to school without the consent of her parents. Her determination gives her the idea of attending Methodist School since it is cheaper than Ladilak where her brother attends, and she needed to be in school by all means. Even her self-confidence makes her courageous to meet Mr. Cole, a Sierra Leonean neighbor, in the school despite his students' mockery of her - \"I came to school - my parents would not send me\" (p. 6). This shows that Adah was ready to endure pains and insults for her to be educated. And, she finds it safe to share her problems with men than women because they \"were so solid\" like she aspires to be. Moreover, Adah was happy her mother was tortured because it made her go to school, and she wasn't bothered about the strokes her father gave her for Ma's benefit.    Also, Igbo's custom of marriage makes Adah grow in determination and confidence. Their women are to degrade themselves to their husbands, whether rich or poor of which she wasn't ready to do. She needed equal rights as men to have a say in her family; and she objects to the idea of getting married to an old man who could only afford her \"high bride price.\" She was unready to be subjugated like other Igbo women, even when it brought a very bad reputation to her. In fact, she refused to be impressed despite the enticement of all the suitors with their new Raleigh bikes with flashy lights. She even stole two shillings given to her for an errand to pay her entrance examination fee in spite knowing it was wrong and never cared about the punishment and hatred she got from Cousin Vincent. She endured the pain from the strokes her cousin also gave her as long as \"she had to go to the Methodist Girls' High School or die\" (p. 17). But she later decided to marry since it was the only way to achieve her dreams.    Nevertheless, the significance of the \"Presence\" boosts Adah's growth in confidence and determination in pursuit of her dreams. It becomes an image in her mind that assures her of a brighter future and her dreams coming to reality. It creates smile on her face because its assurance suits her dreams. For instance, Adah heard the Presence telling her that she will attend one of the best schools and be successful which came true. Adah did the entrance examination with a large number of students with the demand of a few students for scholarship. And fortunately, she was among the chosen five students that was awarded scholarships. Notwithstanding, she felt the Presence no more and realized that it was just an imagination that came out of her determination to live in London which has already left her when her dream came to reality.    Furthermore, Adah's realization of racial segregation in the Western culture and of her marital life contribute to her growth in confidence and determination. She noticed that life in England was different from that in Nigeria, that is, minor things are taken seriously which almost shorten her dreams and belief in education. Starting with her first meeting with Francis who enlightened her about the idea of second class citizen, her disappointment of his poverty life as a black man, their inability to get a foster mother for her children, the rejection of her family to get an apartment, and so on. Despite all of these differences, she never gives up on the society till she finds herself lucky to be employed as a librarian in the city. Aside this, she suffers several ill-treatments from her husband who never cared about her and the children except for himself. She was determined that her marital suffering will be of the past which made her endure pains until Francis burnt her manuscript.    Her pursuit of a writing career strengthens her confidence and determination that she faced her husband for killing it. She refuses to be vulnerable like other women who had lose hope in themselves. Her hope for a brighter future instigates her old dream which makes her attempt writing. Even when she knew she was not a professional writer, she believed in herself as she was able to write a manuscript called The Bride Price which she learnt from a copy of Teach Yourself to Write, \"Write; go on and do it, you can write\" (p. 174) was what she keeps hearing. She also vows to love and care for her children since Francis neglects them. And, she defends this at the magistrate court where she told the judge, \"Don't worry, sir. The children are mine, and that is enough. I shall never let them down as long as I am alive\" (p. 185). The use of \"will\" shows that Adah is fully grown in determination and confidence for a brighter future.    In conclusion, this essay has shown Adah's growth in confidence and determination in pursuit of her dreams through the societal rejection of her gender, her desire to be in school, Igbo's custom of marriage, the significance of the Presence, racial segregation, her marital life, her writing career and her vow to cater for children in absence of her husband, Francis.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section A>3","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"3","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN PROSE","question":"ALEX AGYEI-AGYIRI: Unexpected Joy at Dawn    Discuss Nii's encounter with I-Put-it-to-me in the novel.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"I-Put-it-to-me, rarely known as Tally O, is an illegal dealer in gold. He is a frustrated citizen whose fear of poverty turns into an excessively greedy human.  He lives in Ghana, too, where some of the main characters like Nii, Joe and Aaron also abide.  Of course, his encounter with Nii brings out the element of irony in the story. Tally O has once met Nii's sister, Mama Orojo, whom she sells fake gold to in the plane. Mama has been deceived by his faked kindness that she forgets to even question his credibility for once. He appears perfect. Mama buys the gold feeling so exhilarated because she thinks she has invested her money in something that will be of immense value to her when she gets back to Nigeria. Unfortunately, the gold turns out to be against her expectation; it's forgery. A taxi driver who takes her from the airport reveal this to her knowledge.    Also, Tally O is a good friend of Joe. They are both involved in the illicit activity of gold dealing. They operate at night after they have been properly hinted on the flexibility of the gold camp and the security that hover it. Even when Mama tells Joe of her experience with I-put-it-to-me in the plane, he does not know that it is Tally O, his friend, that dupes her. It is also quite surprising that throughout the course of the story, this mystery is unravelled.     The day that Nii sets to leave Ghana for Nigeria is the same day that Mama Orojo arrives in Ghana. Despite the fact that they have both encountered similar persons, none of them takes cognisance of their resemblance till they are finally apart again. Joe knows Nii from Expense Bank so he is able to tell Mama Orojo some things about Nii when she finally confides her main mission in Ghana in him. The few encounters between the duo have a huge impact on Joe who develops a strong feeling of love for Mama at instance. He confesses his love to her on one of their searches for Nii and she accepts wholeheartedly. When Joe tells Tally O of his desire to leave their dubious life and settle down with Mama Orojo, Tally O is displeased.  He feels there's more to life than marriage and that Joe may be constraining himself by getting married. On their final operation at the mining centre, Tally O's head is cut off with an axe because he's trapped and his screaming could get them exposed and caught.    From the aforementioned, it could be deduced that the encounter between these two characters is symbolic as well as suspenseful. It also helps to build the plot and subsequently connect other characters.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section A>4","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"4","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN PROSE","question":"ALEX AGYEI-AGYIRI: Unexpected Joy at Dawn  Consider Mama Orojo's relationship with her church members in Amen Kristi.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Mama Orojo's relationship with her church members is a good and enviable one. She is so passionate about her evangelical duty that she carries it out without nonchalance or fear. One of the members of the church is Ibuk. In most parts of the evangelical duties, Ibuk and Mama Orojo are together till when, on a very sad day, Ibuk loses her life in a fire attack spurred by a religious riot.     Apart from Ibuk, Mama Orojo is able to bring Tom Monday into Amen Kristi. Though Tom Monday admires her, the manner at which she presents her religious arguments makes him accept the ministry wholeheartedly. Also, when Mama returns from Ghana, she goes to meet some of these members in the hope of gladdening their hearts with the news of her marriage to Joe; however, the Chairman refuses to accept her marriage for he sees it as a disloyalty to one's country as well as God. Though Mama is sad on hearing this, she still tries to convince the Chairman the more, and, eventually, desires a reason for the blatant opposition. Her good relationship with the church keeps her from staying away from them even when she is old enough to decide for herself. She still goes ahead to get engaged in the voting system proposed. Though she loses to the opposition party in the votes cast on her marriage decision, she still goes her ahead to get her wish fulfilled many because she upholds the belief that religion should not be a barrier for marriage, and that if people are to be engaged based on only religion and tribe, then the religion institutions will wallow in the discrimination it actually sets out to curtail.    Mama's release of the chairman that is trapped in the religious riot fire incident depicts her as a good religious woman who innately understands people. She could have decided to have her revenge on him for bitterly going against her decision to marry Joe, who is from another tribe and religion. But she understands that even the Chairman has nothing against her personally; he is only scared that the image of the church may be badly painted by her act and he somewhat feels Tom Monday will make a good husband for her.     In all, it's apparent that the relationship between Mama Orojo and the members of her church is a good one. She's highly respected for her effort towards facilitating the growth and development of the church, and, in most cases, always given enviable position to hold.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section B>5","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"5","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN PROSE","question":"RALPH ELLISON: Invisible Man    Comment on the character and role of Mary in the novel.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"After the narrator's experience at the Liberty paint factory hospital, Mary comes into the narrator's life as a motherly figure. She showers him with kindness and generosity. She understands his need for help; thus, she takes him into her home and treats him back to good health. Mary serves as the figure that backs the narrator up. She believes in him to be an upholder of their race. From the authorial vision, it is no surprise that she bears the name, Mary.    From the first meeting, the narrator views Mary as a mother figure as well as his guide and anchor. He also appreciates her place in his life. However, upon meeting Brother Jack and his involvement in the brotherhood; his perspective of everything, Mary inclusive, begins to change. It is at this point that the narrator begins to note the flaws - one of which is Mary being loquacious. Initially, he enjoys her cooking; now the narrator complains of the cabbage diet. Her home that naturally served as comfort to him, now becomes discomfortable as he notices the noise, poverty and filth around.    The narrator finally leaves Mary without a goodbye as he believes she will do well alone because she is black. Overall, Mary symbolically represents the black heritage and race. She represents the courage and dignity of the black people and in the narrator's bid to discard this heritage, he leaves Mary behind.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section B>6","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"6","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN PROSE","question":"RALPH ELLISON: Invisible Man  Examine the narrator's experiences at the eviction.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The narrator had just met a street vendor selling baked yams and experiences a nostalgic home feeling (home =the South). He buys three to eat as he walks down the street as he feels no need to hide his identity as a southern; part of which has been denial of his love for this food. He imagines his classmates' shock at seeing him have this food that represent Southern culture. He scorns them for distancing themselves from the food all in the name of neglecting their own culture. It is at this point that the narrator encounters an eviction. He saw two white men bringing out the possession of an old black couple. Other blacks stood around as this is a common occurrence. The old woman calls the narrator's attention to her predicament and this propelled him to react.    The old woman tried to return into the apartment to pray but the white men stopped her. A scuffle ensued at this point and the old woman fell. This angered the bystanders. The narrator tries to stop an impending violence from erupting as he pleaded for calmness and explained the consequence of a possible violent action. The narrator gives an emotional speech against dispossession and this urged the bystanders to stop the eviction and return the possession of the old couple back into the apartment.    It did not take long after for the police to arrive and the narrator fled as he knew he was at the forefront of this breach of law and faces a possible arrest. It is after narrowly escaping the police that the narrator meets Brother Jack who introduces him to the brotherhood which the narrator initially rebuffs.    This part of the novel is significant as the narrator has gone from one extreme to the other. The narrator has come at the back of denying his black identity to embracing this identity; first through the food scenario and further reaffirmed by his stance at the eviction. The actions of the blacks at the eviction also illustrate the powerful, although largely unacknowledged, role of black people in the struggle for freedom and equality. At the core, the narrator's emotional speech solidifies his individuality in the context of the collective black American experience, one that he has just come to embrace.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section B>7","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"7","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN PROSE","question":"EMILY BRONTE: Wuthering Heights    Comment on the importance of setting in the novel.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"THE IMPORTANCE OF SETTING IN EMILY BRONTE'S WUTHERING HEIGHTS    The setting of a piece of literature is the time and place in which the story takes place. The definition of setting can also include social statuses, weather, historical period, and details about immediate surroundings. Settings can be real or fictional, or a combination of both real and fictional elements.     Wuthering Heights is comprised of two main settings, one obviously being Wuthering Heights. The other is Thrushcross Grange, and together they create a perfect atmosphere filled with conflicts that match up with the plot. Wuthering Heights is a setting filled with passion and strength, but it is also filled with doomed intensity. Thrushcross Grange is filled with civility and kindness, but is filled with snobbishness. The two are complete opposites of each other; they are foils for each other in the sense that the two heighten each other's characteristics. The inhabitants of Wuthering Heights and Thrushcross Grange are perfect representatives of everything the two settings represent.    The story is realistic set in the harsh and isolated Yorkshire moors in Northern England, Wuthering Heights practically makes a character out of its geography. The \"present day\" action of the novel takes place from 1801-1802 with the retrospective plot events occurring over the previous thirty years. All of the action happens in a small, isolated, and wild area dominated by two grand estates owned by neighboring families. Because of the geographical isolation, many conventional social rules don't seem to apply at the Heights, which is part of why Lockwood is often shocked by what he learns about the local residents.    The setting is also dominated by stormy, unpleasant weather. Lockwood explains that the word \"Wuthering\" refers to \"the atmospheric tumult to which its station is exposed in stormy weather.\" However, the Yorkshire moors can be a beautiful place as well as a violent one. As Lockwood reflects when he returns to Yorkshire at a more pleasant time of year, \"In winter, nothing is drearier, in summer nothing more divine.\" Thus, the setting also serves as a parallel to the love of Cathy and Heathcliff, stormy and devastating yet divinely powerful. This choice of setting allows for an intense and focused plot that is concentrated on a small cast of characters.     The novel's setting also plays a huge role in the lives of the new generation which consists of Cathy, the late Catherine and Edgar's daughter; Linton, the late Isabelle and Heathcliff's son; and Hareton, Hindley's son. When speaking with Linton about a perfect day in the moors, Cathy and Linton have two very different ideas of perfect. Cathy wants a lively, exciting day at the moors while all Linton wants is peace and rest. This shows how incompatible and how contrasting their characters are. Cathy is headstrong and lively like her mother, while Linton is weak and whiny like his mother.     In all, the main importance of the setting in the story is that it marks it genre out. It is the setting that enables us to quickly tag it a Gothic novel. It also gives us some hints about the events that will likely take place.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2021>Prose>Section B>8","subject":"Literature","year":"2021","type":"Theory","sub_label":"8","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN PROSE","question":"EMILY BRONTE: Wuthering Heights  Examine the relationship between Lockwood and Heathcliff in the novel.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN LOCKWOOD AND HEATHCLIFF IN WUTHERING HEIGHTS    The relationship that exists between Lockwood and Heathcliff is a complex and unfriendly one. Lockwood is the new tenant who pays Heathcliff a visit twice at the Wuthering Heights. Mr. Lockwood is described as a wealthy gentleman who has just come to spend a year in the country at Thrushcross Grange. Heathcliff, as the owner of Thrushcross Grange, is Lockwood's landlord. Lockwood meets Heathcliff at Wuthering Heights, Heathcliff's home atop the English moors. Lockwood is struck at once by the beauty and isolation of the area His two visits to the Wuthering Heights are met with hostility and contempt. Even the male servant, Joseph, whom Lockwood thinks will help in calming Heathcliff's unfriendly nature contributes more to the adverse effect Lockwood faces at the Heights.    Initially, Mr Lockwood has thought that Heathcliff is a philanthropist who has a kind heart. This thought has sprung from Lockwood's poor observant skill. However, Lockwoord does not get to know more about Heathcliff till he visits him for a second time. Lockwood is clearly blind to the reality of the situation, although the extent of his misinterpretations is not fully realized. He is the first of many narrators (later in the story) to tell the story from a point of view that is neither omniscient nor unbiased. In fact, one could have mistaken him as the protagonist of the whole story.    On the second visit to Wuthering Heights, Lockwood gets a better sense of its strange inhabitants. Stranded at Heathcliff's home during a snowstorm, Lockwood finds his host anything but hospitable. Zillah, one of Heathcliff's servants, escorts Lockwood to a bedroom. In the bedroom, Lockwood first encounters the name of Catherine as he peruses her books. Later in the night, he experiences a nightmare or a ghostly vision, which elicits an odd response from Heathcliff. Heathcliff begs the ghost to enter Lockwood's bedroom-a plea that Lockwood does not understand at all. The next day, Heathcliff agrees to guide Lockwood back to the Grange, and Lockwood is more than happy to leave Wuthering Heights at last.    Lockwood is the one who first presents the readers with a slice of Heathcliff's heinous and brutal nature. Through the events unfolded in their encounters, the readers get to see their relationship as one which is unadmirable and that which will eventually end in disaster. When Lockwood is attacked by some violent dogs at the Heights, Heathcliff blames him for not minding his business rather than sympathizing with him or scolding the horrible dogs.    The way Heathcliff relates with Lockwood in the first and second encounters makes him to be interested in persuading Nelly to tell him everything about Heathcliff. Heathcliff's past is totally revealed and Lockwoord comes to understand the reasons behind his actions.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"}];